ement practices, inculcate moral and civic values, and develop a strategy for containing union activities and strikes. In an integrated analysis of gender ideology and ideologies of nationalism and ethnicity, Faison shows how this discourse on women's wage work both produced and reflected anxieties about women's social roles in modern Japan.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aPersonnel managementzJapanxHistory. 0aWomen textile workerszJapanxHistory. 0aWomenxEmploymentzJapanxHistory. 7aHISTORY / Asia / General.2bisacsh  a20th century japan.  afactory managers.  agender equality in japan.  agender roles.  agender women studies.  aideal woman.  ainterwar textile industry.  ajapanese femininity.  ajapanese feminism.  ajapanese feminist studies.  alabor relations.  alabor-management practices.  asocial reformers.  asociety and industry.  awomen social roles.  awomens wages.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z97831106904220 cprintz978052025296740uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052093418440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520934184423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520934184/original  a978-3-11-069042-2  University of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-UCY